title: 12C(p,p`)12C reaction at medium energies: Large momentum transfer and density dependent forces

momentum transfer and density dependent forces

x4freetext: Indiana University Cyclotron Facility.
The proton beam polarization was typically 70%.
Both natural and enriched self-supporting 12C targets
were used, ranging in thickness from 2 mg/cm2 for
forward angle measurements to 132 mg/cm2 at the
largest angles.
Magnetic spectrograph (QDDM),
helical wire chamber, and an array of two plastic
scintillators.
The scattered protons were detected
in the focal plane of a magnetic spectrograph (QDDM)
with the aid of a helical wire chamber for position
information, and an array of two plastic
scintillators for particle identification. The
angular range covered was from 6 to 156 degrees in
the center of mass system. At 160 MeV incident energy
this corresponds to a range of transferred momentum q
of 50 to 1000 MeV/c. Beam currents of up to 200 nA
were used, except at forward angles where the beam
intensity had to be reduced in order to keep the dead
time of the data acquisition system below 10%.
Contributions from accidental coincidences to the
background under the peak of interest were
non-negligible only at the smallest and largest
angles. However, since the cross section for
inelastic scattering to the final 2+ state at
backward angles is considerably larger than for
elastic scattering, background contributions were
much less severe for the inelastic case.
Small corrections (1-2%) were applied to the data,
taking into account the finite acceptance angle of
the spectrograph, which varied between delta theta
+-0.52 and +-0.97 degrees.

x4code.headerHelp: Error in value of quantity, defined under ERR-ANALYS

x4freetext: The quoted uncertainties of the
measurements were obtained by combining the
statistical errors with (i) an uncertainty of the
cross section due to the background subtraction
(estimated to be 4% for intermediate angles and 8%
for both extreme forward and backward angles), and
(ii) an inaccuracy of 0.05 degree in the angle
setting of the spectrograph resulting in a small
contribution to the error of both sigma and A. An
overall normalization error of the cross sections of
5-10% was deduced by comparing overlapping data
points measured with different target thicknesses.
The latter error has not been included in the final
errors.
Background subtraction.
